column123: I highly value authenticity and loyalty, and they are deeply ingrained in me. For the self and for psychological happiness, it's important to be true to yourself - that's something I see in truly happy people and I strive to be completely myself to be satisfied with life. Loyalty to me is vital. A person needs to remain steadfast and cherish relationships, which to me, is shown through loyalty. Moody is my worst quality since I think being more even-keel is preferable, but I know that I can vary in moods, sometimes without a good reason. I don't think it's becoming and I know that's not something I generally see as a good thing in others. Being stubborn isn't completely bad; however, it has to do a lot with pride which gets in the way of realizing early on when it's a good time to see something from a different perspective or when to relent instead of continuing to hold a grudge. Again, it's not necessarily a quality I value in others, and thus I don't value it in myself.

I also don't give up very easily with hard tasks. I think this shows a lot of discipline and willpower to get what I want. When I listed strong as my other best quality, I meant emotionally strong, not physically strong. Don't get me wrong, I am athletic and I can lift things, but I am strong in the mental sense of the word. column123: I am kind to others, which facilitates strong and trusting relationships with others. I am also determined in the work I do, which allows me to complete many tasks well and to the best of my abilities. Sometimes being straightforward can be a bad trait depending on the situation or the person that I am communicating with. I am also a quiet person before I feel totally comfortable in a situation, which can prevent me from developing relationships quickly.

I love to make people laugh - and once I know them enough to use situations as humorous material, I go for it. I enjoy wordplay, hypothesizing the ridiculous as a form of humor, and making witty observations on the world or people around me. Friends have commented on this trait so I have become aware that it is a large part of my identity in certain circles. I also care deeply about the people in my life, and enjoy going out of my way to surprise or delight them when they least expect it. Even if I don't always say it I am very attached to my friends and family, and care strongly about my relationships with them. I also care strongly in other realms, such as in work that I am passionate about.  I am well aware when I need to exercise patience and find it hard to do so. Sometimes I feel rushed when needless time is taken up with waiting or doing things inefficiently. I wish I could be as patient as some of my friends and family that I know, and I try to take a breather when things become frustrating. At times I can also be selfish, usually only with little things - getting an extra cookie, the better seat, or listening to the music I prefer on the radio. On bigger, more important things I am all for compromise, but I do like to fight for the better/self-serving option in daily occurrences. This is another thing I have tried to work on letting go, and letting those little things be little as they should be.

column123: I said my compassion for others is one of my best traits because I like that I tend to care about others more than myself. I wouldn't want to be one of those people who can pass by a homeless person on the street without a second glance. Compassion gives live a better purpose than just trying to reach my own goals. It help drive a lot of the decision I make. I said my intelligence as my other best trait because it has always helped define who I am. I like that I am able to think about difficult problems and I really enjoy learning. I guess I would have to qualify this choice and say that I really like that I am both intelligent and determined. Simply being smart is not going to get anyone anywhere if they aren't willing to work hard to apply that intelligence and further themselves. My intelligence, plus my tendency to always push myself further, has earned me a lot of incredible opportunities and blessings so I am very thankful for these traits.

Being positive and social has helped me develop as a person. It's helped me achieve success and reach all my goals. It has also kept me a better person by grounding me in my values as I grew up. Being lazy and aloof has hindered me from completing some of my tasks. It's more difficult to accomplish goals when you don't have the motivation to do anything. Also, being aloof has kept me from forming some close relationships that could have become good friendships.

I am always doing things for others. I do not count what I do for my friends or husband. I also work in social work where I give a lot of my time to help others. Generosity comes naturally to me. I am funny because I love making other people laugh, I have a great sense of humor and I know what to say to get a room full of people to laugh. I am anxious, I stress a lot over little things and life in general.I have a lack of confidence in what I do, I always question myself and my capabilities in accomplishing a task.

column123: I said that I'm down to earth, because I try not to think of myself as better than anyone else.  I try to get to know people before I pass judgement on them.  I try to give support and understanding to friends and family.  I try to relate to their situations and offer advice.   I said that I am senisive, because many times I find myself taking things people say or do personally, when in fact it's usually a misunderstanding.  I can be hot-headed at times, which stems from being over-sensitive.

I consider myself to be quite imaginative, and people tend to admire my somewhat zany creative projects.  I once made a nine-part video series about a magic lemon, which garnered positive feedback.  I also wrote a novel about a man trapped inside his own insane imagination.  I would say that I have a somewhat restless mind, and I like both imagining new stories and hearing the stories of others.   I think I'm quite caring towards the ones I love.  Although I get easily frustrated at them sometimes, I always make an effort to improve the lives of my family, friends and romantic partners.  I am usually very accommodating in relationships, focusing on my partner rather than myself. I can be a bit spiteful at times, holding grudges unnecessarily.  I will try to take petty revenge on those who wrong me instead of finding a constructive solution. I can also be a bit lazy.  My room is always disorganized and I sometimes do not study enough.  I also have to bribe myself to exercise.

I try to always think of others and how they might feel in any given situation. I do my best to be thankful for what I have and make the world a better place by being kind and caring to my friends as well as strangers. I think that being funny makes most situations in life more fun and enjoyable. Although i often do not try to be the clown or anything like that, people often tell me that I am funny and I really enjoy making people laugh.  I think that my two worst qualities go hand in hand. I have a tendency to judge people too harshly (although I often change my opinion of people quickly). Because I can be judgmental, I also have a tendency to get annoyed too easily which I think can be very off putting to some people.

column123: I am passionate in EVERYTHING that I am doing, which is why I'm dedicated to it. I decided that I don't want to waste any of my time, here at WashU especially. My first two years went by way too fast, and time will only get faster. So, I'm only doing things that I love and that I can completely throw myself into and enjoy.  With this mentality, I also have no time to waste -- on people included. I hate it when people have no respect for my time. When people are disrespectful, I judge them hardcore. I wish I did not, but it at least seems reasonable to judge them on a personal experience of disprespectfulness with me. I want everything perfect an have a certain way of doing MY things. Maintaining relaxed composure in almost any situation is certainly helpful, and is something a number of friends and family have commented on.  Personally I'm not sure if it's calm composure or downright indifference, but I almost never get really upset, worried, or lose my temper in stressful situations.  I like to think it saves me a lot of time and energy. It is not entirely unrelated to my laziness, which is a bad quality all around.  Nothing good comes from laziness and I can put forth my life so far as a testament to that.  Even as I type this, I am mildly surprised by my willingness to do it at all.  But of course, if it is for science.  Cliche as it may sound, sentience is a gift that is both blessing and a curse.  Kind of like money: As long as you know you have it, it's a source of satisfaction - but the more you use it, the emptier you feel.  It shaped me into the person I am today, which is an improvement from the lump of flesh I was 23 years ago - but not THAT much an improvement. Sentience allows me to do things, then realize it is meaningless afterall.  It helps me visualize the possibilities, wonders and the future - all the way to my inevitable death.  I don't really like it, but it's what defines me, and it keeps things interesting enough in life.

column122: too busy/don't live in the moment enough
column123: I really care for others--almost to the point where I care about others more than myself. I am involved in a student group on campus that trained me as a peer counselor, where I talk with and console clients that come into our office or call on our phone line. My friends have always turned to me when they needed to talk, but since I have joined this student group, my friends and family immediately turn to me. I love to help others through difficult times, and I am really glad that I received proper training to make the most impact; however, a lot of my time is spent helping others with their concerns. As a result, I often feel that I don't live in the moment or think about myself often enough. Although I would much rather give my time helping others and making sure those around me are doing well, it is a double-headed sword.  Furthermore, I have devoted a lot my time to volunteer work that I find immensely fulfilling. It really is important to me that others less fortunate than I am are receiving assistance in some form. I honestly believe that my compassion and sense of caring for friends, family, and strangers is one of my most redeeming qualities.  On the other hand, I do often feel lazy and that I waste my time doing activities that don't amount to enough in the long run. I am a very busy person--I am involved in many student groups and take about 18 credits a semester--and I think being busy is a fault. Even when I have free time, I tend to waste it by lying in bed or watching TV when there are many other things I should be doing. I feel like, in the long run, I am not taking full advantage of what my life has to offer.

When communicating with others, especially people I don't know, I am always as friendly as I can be, and make sure not to brush people off rudely even when I am not interested in pursuing a friendship or relationship with them. Kindness is very important to me, and I want to intentionally cause anyone harm. With my friends, I am someone they can tell anything, and I will lend an ear to their struggles, problems, etc, and can be a source of some comfort and advice. Along these same lines, my friends and family can depend on me to help with almost anything whenever I can, from tutoring help to moving. I make sure to be there for the people closest to me.  I have a very assertive personality, and talk a lot, which sometimes can make me a tough pill to swallow. I bring a lot of energy to most situations, and as a result can overpower conversations. I often find myself talking too much at the expense of listening to what others have to say. I also tend to see things as very fixed, especially people, and am quick to like or dislike individuals. I also tend to pass judgments on others' personalities pretty quickly, and keep things pretty black and white in my head when it comes to other people.

column123: I think adaptability is one of my best qualities because I understand that very few things in life are stable and remain the same. Most conditions, whether they be in work or friendship, are subject to change over time due to a variety of forces, so I am great at remaining calm and anticipating those changes. Part of this is that I know what it feels like (and I am comfortable with the feeling) of being let down or disappointed and moving on. I have received a fair number of job offer rejections and know what it is like to under-perform in school, so I have really learned to role with the punches that life throws at me. I think of times as a catering manager where I was forced to be adaptable to the whims of our clients and the time that my dad fractured his neck in Costa Rica and I had to step in as the 13 year old translator for his medical treatment as foundational experiences in fostering one of my best qualities which is adaptability.  I am tenacious because I am the ultimate competitor when I am up against myself and my personal limits. I am tenacious partly to prove to others that I can exceed expectations of performance, but I also am just constantly thinking of how I can do better or improve. Being tenacious can be exhausting mentally and physically, because no one can always be outperforming their last achievement, but I get a charge out of seeing myself improve (even marginally) with each attempt I give something, whether it being a work assignment or a rock climbing route. I think that tenacity is one of my best traits because it applies to all my life's endeavors.  Being easily distracted is one of my worst qualities, but also something that is rooted in something I am proud of: my diversity of interests. I am a curious person and I am invigorated by all knowledge, so sometimes it is difficult for me to stay focused particularly when I lack direction and instruction. It is really when I am left up to my own devices and forced to design my own strategy of accomplishing something where distraction becomes a problem, and I wish I was better at being self-motivated on tasks that are important to me.  Indecisiveness is another "bad" quality of mine because it means that I feel like I have lost many opportunities because of my inability to make a quick decision or go after exactly what I want. I tend to overanalyze decisions and think that cons outweigh pros and use that as an excuse not to do anything at all

column123: I want to make the world a better place, and so I love it when I am able to make my community a better place through what I give to those around me. I firstly give them my attention -- I am very often sensitive to the moods and desires of those around me -- and then as best I can I give them a positive outlook and confidence, and empower them to do their best. I feel like if I can maintain that positivity in my interactions with myself and the world, I'll be able to go as far as I possibly can in life. And because my sensitivity to others is so keen, I feel like it will be one of my best assets in doing what I want to do.     The biggest detriments, then, are those listed above. Often times I have trouble pushing myself to do what I want to do on a larger scale, the ability for which I describe as self-discipline. I feel like if I can foster discipline within myself, I can push myself to be better than my undesirable habits and tendencies.     When it comes to developing self-discipline however, as well as various other fields (like being creative, persevering on assignments, or doing the things that are hardest for me, like writing or paperwork), I feel like I'm sometimes set back by uncertainty as to whether I can accomplish the thing I want to do. I think I sometimes don't work as hard as I could if I already knew I could do something. If I were to charge into these hardest things with full confidence, I would better be able to keep a healthy, positive attitude that I know helps me so much.
